00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:47.310
So starting right away
with Einstein,

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:49.220
so this is a paper from 1915.

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:51.930
I don't speak German, but
this basically says, you know,

00:03:51.930 --> 00:03:53.530
on the theory of relativity

00:03:53.530 --> 00:03:56.200
or general relativity
and general relativity.

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:58.900
So people associate Einstein
with this idea of relativity.

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:00.200
And some people don't realize

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:02.370
that there's actually two
theories of relativity.

00:04:02.370 --> 00:04:05.610
And the special relativity one
is the one that happened first.

00:04:05.610 --> 00:04:08.830
And it's the one that told us about
this idea that there's nothing

00:04:08.830 --> 00:04:11.190
that can go faster than
the speed of light.

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:13.110
And that's one of the
sort of postulates

00:04:13.110 --> 00:04:15.590 position:56%
of the theory of special relativity.

00:04:15.590 --> 00:04:19.810
And that was a very successful,
successful theory and in made,

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:21.840
you know, Einstein famous in
sort of scientific circles.

00:04:21.840 --> 00:04:26.470 position:56%
But he wasn't really famous in the
general public circles at that time.

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:28.970
But one of the things that
was pretty quickly realized is

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:31.880
that Newton's theory or gravity
which, again, was very successful

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:35.800
because we could use it to
predict the motion of the planets,

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:37.530
didn't match with special
relatively.

00:04:37.530 --> 00:04:41.500
And, in particular, if you
had an object, you know,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:44.480
some piece of mass, and you
moved it, the information

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:46.030
that that had moved, you know,

00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:48.020
in terms of the gravitational
information,

00:04:48.020 --> 00:04:50.170
in Newton's theory
propagated instantly.

00:04:50.170 --> 00:04:53.710
So, a way to think about it is
that if you were to take the sun

00:04:53.710 --> 00:04:56.490
and just, you know,
suddenly make it disappear,

00:04:56.490 --> 00:04:59.320
the Earth would instantaneously
know that it was being,

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:00.760
getting that gravitational field.

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:02.060
And that's the way that it's --

00:05:02.060 --> 00:05:04.280
that sort of information
would be propagating faster

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:05.580
than the speed of light.

00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:07.560
And Einstein said, gosh,
that just can't work.

00:05:07.560 --> 00:05:11.370 position:56%
That doesn't, you know, that doesn't
jive with special relativity.

00:05:11.370 --> 00:05:13.810 position:56%
And this is sort of showing you that
-- the genius that it's Einstein.

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:15.110
You know, he doesn't say, well,

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:16.410
maybe my theory's wrong
and Newton's right.

00:05:16.410 --> 00:05:19.020
He goes, well, maybe our whole
idea of gravity is wrong, right?

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:22.650 position:56%
And it takes him years and years and
years to finally figure out and come

00:05:22.650 --> 00:05:26.000
up with this theory of general
relativity which I'll try

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.160
to explain a little bit
in the following way.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:30.360
So we know general
relativity's about gravity.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:31.820
And if you usually ask
people, you say, well,

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:33.120
how do we know about gravity?

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:34.420
And they say, well, that's easy.

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:38.040
I just drop something and
there you go, gravity, right?

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:40.470
However, you know, you can
imagine if you had a skydiver,

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:42.560
and I'm being -- this
is a physicist skydiver,

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:45.860
so it's perfectly frictionless
which is not good for it's --

00:05:45.860 --> 00:05:48.300
not good for skydiving but
good for this illustration.

00:05:48.300 --> 00:05:50.610
If a skydiver releases
the ball, nothing happens.

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:51.910
It just sits there, right?

00:05:51.910 --> 00:05:54.120
Because they're both
accelerating at the same rate.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:56.450
And so, you know, I think
everyone would agree

00:05:56.450 --> 00:06:00.000
that somehow gravity's involved
in that problem, but, you know,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.160
somehow it doesn't seem to
be apparent to the skydiver

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.090
when he's measuring this, right?

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:08.940
And so to make a long story short,
one of the things that turns

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:11.850
out to really understand the
difference between just the effects

00:06:11.850 --> 00:06:14.350
of acceleration, that is,
doing your measurement

00:06:14.350 --> 00:06:18.910
in an accelerating
laboratory versus gravitation,

00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:21.190
you need to make a
measurement that's not local.

00:06:21.190 --> 00:06:22.630
That is, you need to
compare measurements

00:06:22.630 --> 00:06:24.420
that happen at different places.

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:26.270 position:56%
And this is an illustration of that.

00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:30.240
So if you have two balls that are
way up high and you drop them,

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:34.220
you notice that they actually don't
drop in exactly parallel lines.

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:36.000
They actually start to get
closer to one another and that's

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:37.760
because they're each
travelling towards the center

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:39.610
of the Earth, not directly down.

00:06:39.610 --> 00:06:42.370
So down is a different
direction when you're over here

00:06:42.370 --> 00:06:44.210
and when you're over here, right?

00:06:44.210 --> 00:06:48.660 position:56%
And it's only -- so an accelerating
frame wouldn't give you that effect.

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:51.150
But gravitation does
give you that effect.

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:52.450
And that's a way to sort

00:06:52.450 --> 00:06:55.490
of unequivocally determine the
difference between the fact

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:58.340 position:56%
that you're just doing a measurement
in an accelerating laboratory

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:00.780
or you're doing a measurement
where there's gravitation.

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:04.350
So this is a really
fundamental idea for any kind

00:07:04.350 --> 00:07:05.650
of gravitational measurement.

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:07.760
You need to make a measurement
over a long distance.

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:09.730
And when you get to
gravitational weight detectors,

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:11.030
which we'll eventually
get to in this talk,

00:07:11.030 --> 00:07:15.420
you'll see that having a separated
distance is really important, okay?

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:18.850
And the mathematical name for this
thing is called geodesic deviation.

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:20.800
And it's this idea that
trajectories that are

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:22.950
in freefall are not parallel.

00:07:22.950 --> 00:07:26.610
That is, they can converge
or diverge.

00:07:26.610 --> 00:07:29.230
So you also hear this
idea of curved spacetime.

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:30.560
So where does this come from?

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:34.210
Well, this comes from this idea
that geometry and the geometry

00:07:34.210 --> 00:07:36.540
of curvature is a nice
way to describe.

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:38.130
It's a perfect example of places

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:41.120
where you have straight
lines that converge.

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:44.310
So you imagine if you have a
person over here on the Equator

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:45.980
and a person over here
on the Equator,

00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:48.330
and they both say they're
going to go north, right,

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:51.310
which on a map projection will
look like it was a straight line,

00:07:51.310 --> 00:07:52.700
they actually come
together, and, in fact,

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:54.250
they meet at the North Pole, right?

00:07:54.250 --> 00:07:58.680
So that's an example of lines that
are straight, that is, you know,

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:02.210
straight lines on the surface of
a sphere that converge, right.

00:08:02.210 --> 00:08:05.190
And the reason they converge
is because the surface

00:08:05.190 --> 00:08:07.000
that they're on is curved, right?

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:08.350
So people can kind of
picture that in their head.

00:08:08.350 --> 00:08:09.980
There's a lot of math behind it.

00:08:09.980 --> 00:08:13.530
But that's the basic idea, right,
is that, that this geometry,

00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:16.940
this idea of curvature, can
be used to describe how things

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:19.880
that are straight lines, just
like those freely-falling balls

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:22.120
that we had in the last scene,
can converge or diverge.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:24.030
And it has to do with
the underlying curvature

00:08:24.030 --> 00:08:26.150
of the system that they're on.

00:08:26.150 --> 00:08:29.950
So Einstein basically extends
that whole idea to space and time.

00:08:29.950 --> 00:08:32.870
And so it's really difficult to
visualize because it's curvature

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:35.750
in four dimensions and so,
you know, it's almost --

00:08:35.750 --> 00:08:38.900
it's effectively impossible
to visualize other than --

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:41.790 position:56%
let's saying we imagine we sort of
suppress one of the other dimensions

00:08:41.790 --> 00:08:45.170
and measure that curvature in
that some sort of extra dimension.

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:46.470
So here you have this idea

00:08:46.470 --> 00:08:47.950
that spacetime is this
sort of rubber sheet.

00:08:47.950 --> 00:08:50.030
You put something massive
like the Earth on it.

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:52.010 position:56%
The Earth deforms that rubber sheet.

00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:54.220
And then the other thing
that's interesting about it is

00:08:54.220 --> 00:08:56.630
that if you have, you know,
any kind of object, you know,

00:08:56.630 --> 00:08:58.360
a ball or even a particle of light,

00:08:58.360 --> 00:09:00.900
it's going to follow one
of these straight lines.

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:04.870
But these straight lines now have
curvature to them that are produced

00:09:04.870 --> 00:09:08.070
by that mass, you know, produced
by the mass of the Earth.

00:09:08.070 --> 00:09:10.550
And so the way we like to say
how general relativity works is

00:09:10.550 --> 00:09:13.380
that matter tells spacetime
how to curve,

00:09:13.380 --> 00:09:15.540
so depending upon the distribution
of matter in the universe,

00:09:15.540 --> 00:09:17.400 position:56%
you get a distribution of curvature.

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:21.110
And curvature, that is, spacetime,
tells matter how move, right?

00:09:21.110 --> 00:09:24.950 position:56%
So if things are in freefall orbits,
their freefall orbits are going

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:27.680
to be affected by the
background curvature of spacetime.

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:30.830
And in equation form this
is Einstein's equation.

00:09:30.830 --> 00:09:32.130
So somebody asked me if I was going

00:09:32.130 --> 00:09:33.920
to show Einstein's
equations, there you go.

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:35.590
It doesn't look so hard, right?

00:09:35.590 --> 00:09:39.010
So this is an object called
the Einstein curvature tensor.

00:09:39.010 --> 00:09:42.450 position:56%
So this is a mathematical
description of, you know, spacetime.

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:44.340
You can write down a
curvature tensor for a ball.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:47.420
You can write it down
for all kinds of things.

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:49.500
And then this is just
some constants.

00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:52.380
And then this other bit here is
called the stress energy tensor.

00:09:52.380 --> 00:09:53.680
It's basically just a way

00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:56.560
to describe how matter is
distributed in the universe.

00:09:56.560 --> 00:09:57.860
So that's really it.

00:09:57.860 --> 00:09:59.160
That's Einstein equations.

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:00.660
Now the hard part is
that this is a set

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:03.040
of coupled nonlinear
differential equations

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:06.890
and there are very few
solutions to these equations

00:10:06.890 --> 00:10:08.190
in terms of closed from solution.

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:10.720
So you kind of have this
very beautiful theory,

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:14.740
but there's very few
beautiful solutions, you know,

00:10:14.740 --> 00:10:17.920 position:56%
if that's one way to think about it.

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:20.160
So, you know, this
would just be some sort

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:22.880
of esoteric interesting thing
for mathematicians if it wasn't

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:24.600 position:56%
for the fact that it actually works.

00:10:24.600 --> 00:10:26.790
And so Einstein himself in 1916,

00:10:26.790 --> 00:10:28.650
so a year after their
first publication,

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:31.600
sort of suggested three tests.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:33.140
These are known as the
three classical tests

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:34.440
of general relativity.

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:37.460 position:56%
And the first one Einstein basically
did himself in that same paper.

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:40.430
And this was because the
planet Mercury had been known

00:10:40.430 --> 00:10:42.290 position:56%
to have an orbit that wasn't closed.

00:10:42.290 --> 00:10:45.920 position:56%
And so, you know, all of our planets
are on a slightly elliptical orbit.

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:48.060
And what you could
watch is that axis

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:50.950
of the ellipse actually processes
around the sun at a very,

00:10:50.950 --> 00:10:53.930
very slow rate -- 40
seconds of arc per century.

00:10:53.930 --> 00:10:55.450
So a second of arc.

00:10:55.450 --> 00:10:58.250 position:56%
So you have 360 degrees in a circle.

00:10:58.250 --> 00:11:00.300
You have 60 minutes in each degree,

00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:03.100
and 60 seconds in each
minute, right?

00:11:03.100 --> 00:11:05.490
So it's a 36-hundredth of a degree.

00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:08.160
And then 40 of those per century.

00:11:08.160 --> 00:11:10.490
Now that's an incredibly
tiny amount but astronomers

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:13.230
in the 19th century were already
able to notice this, right?

00:11:13.230 --> 00:11:15.380
So maybe they measured
it as 38 instead of 40,

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:16.930
but they were already
able to measure those.

00:11:16.930 --> 00:11:20.150
And Einstein found that the GR
immediately just predicted this,

00:11:20.150 --> 00:11:23.770
and explained why, if you
do the body problem in GR,

00:11:23.770 --> 00:11:25.840
that you actually get
this procession.

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:28.550
And it shows it most in Mercury
because Mercury gets closest

00:11:28.550 --> 00:11:32.720
to the sun, and so the GR effects
are biggest when you get nearby.

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:34.590 position:56%
The other one -- and again, this is,

00:11:34.590 --> 00:11:37.190
this made him like
pretty famous, right?

00:11:37.190 --> 00:11:39.890 position:56%
But the one that really kicked him
off was this idea of this deflection

00:11:39.890 --> 00:11:41.260
of light by massive bodies.

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:44.870
And so in 1916 he predicts this.

00:11:44.870 --> 00:11:49.350
It turns out that there's a
major solar eclipse in 1919.

00:11:49.350 --> 00:11:50.830
We have another one
coming up next year.

00:11:50.830 --> 00:11:53.240
This shows you sort of how, kind
of how rare these things are.

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:55.360
And this guy, Arthur
Eddington, observed this.

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:56.790
Here's a <i>Washington
Times </i>, you know,

00:11:56.790 --> 00:11:58.350
are the stars really
where we see them?

00:11:58.350 --> 00:12:00.360
And basically they could
see this deflection

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:02.800
of the starlight exactly
as Einstein predicted.

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:04.100
Actually, it was interesting.

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:06.340
It took a couple of years but he
actually had to factor two mistake

00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:09.420
in his prediction which he was able
to correct between his prediction

00:12:09.420 --> 00:12:11.940
and the actual opportunity
to observe the eclipse.

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:15.130
And this is what really
makes Einstein famous, right?

00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:18.260
The third test that he proposed
is this thing called gravitational

00:12:18.260 --> 00:12:20.890
redshift which is the idea
that if you send some light

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:24.560 position:56%
out of a gravitational field it will
change its color due to the fact

00:12:24.560 --> 00:12:27.910 position:56%
that it has to lose energy when it's
leaving the gravitational field.

00:12:27.910 --> 00:12:30.890
It took, whoops, it took
until 1959 before Pound

00:12:30.890 --> 00:12:32.790
and Rebka were actually able
to make that measurement.

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:35.860
So this is starting to get
you an idea of how long --

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:39.010
how far ahead the theory was
of the technology, right.

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:41.390
And that's the theme
for the rest of this.

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:44.700
So I mentioned that in Einstein's
equations there's very few closed

00:12:44.700 --> 00:12:46.000
form solutions.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.670
But there's one solution which
Einstein himself recognized

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:50.170
which is a wave solution.

00:12:50.170 --> 00:12:52.440
So this is what we call
gravitational waves.

00:12:52.440 --> 00:12:55.600
And so here's, again,
another paper from Einstein,

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:59.340
again a single-author paper, and
he finds out that these waves --

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:01.370
so, basically, mathematically,

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:04.000
the equations will
admit a wave solution.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:05.910
That solves the equations, right?

00:13:05.910 --> 00:13:08.950
And so he says, well, gosh,
what's the speed of these waves?

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:10.600
And when he works it out he
goes that's the speed of light.

00:13:10.600 --> 00:13:11.900
He goes, well, that's
kind of interesting.

00:13:11.900 --> 00:13:14.800
Maybe that's the way that
gravity can be compatible

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:16.240
with special relativity, right?

00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:18.520
It's a way that gravitational
information can be propagated

00:13:18.520 --> 00:13:21.300
across the universe is
in gravitational waves.

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:23.650
And, you know, there was a lot
of debate here because this sort

00:13:23.650 --> 00:13:26.200
of shows you how difficult
that the math is.

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:28.650
Einstein and others, and actually
Einstein himself went back

00:13:28.650 --> 00:13:30.270
and forth about, you
know, is this real,

00:13:30.270 --> 00:13:32.570
is this a mathematical
artifact, is it real?

00:13:32.570 --> 00:13:35.190
And Eddington, the very
same guy that had made

00:13:35.190 --> 00:13:37.050
that eclipse measurement,
sort of quipped

00:13:37.050 --> 00:13:39.710
that gravitational waves
propagate at the speed of thought.

00:13:39.710 --> 00:13:41.420
So, basically, the idea that
they're not real, right?

00:13:41.420 --> 00:13:44.050
There just this sort of
figment of the imagination.

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:48.010
And this debate, you know, again,
is confined to this really sort

00:13:48.010 --> 00:13:50.590
of small circle of theoretical
physicists that are working

00:13:50.590 --> 00:13:53.440
on relativity, a very new science.

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:54.740
So what would they look like?

00:13:54.740 --> 00:13:57.740
Well, they would be
transverse to their propagation.

00:13:57.740 --> 00:14:02.020
So, basically, the waves stretch
and squeeze space and time.

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:04.750
And they stretch and squeeze them
in a direction that's orthogonal

00:14:04.750 --> 00:14:06.510
to the way the wave is propagating.

00:14:06.510 --> 00:14:09.220
So imagine a wave is going
into our screen here,

00:14:09.220 --> 00:14:11.670
and you see that they
stretch and they squeeze.

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:14.990 position:56%
And they're actually area preserving
which is kind of interesting.

00:14:14.990 --> 00:14:16.540
So they stretch on one axis

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:18.740
at the same time they're
squeezing on the other one.

00:14:18.740 --> 00:14:20.800
And then they do the opposite.

00:14:20.800 --> 00:14:22.890
They travel at the speed
of light as I mentioned.

00:14:22.890 --> 00:14:24.350
And they have two polarizations.

00:14:24.350 --> 00:14:28.270
We call this one plus because it
has axes that are sort of plus.

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:30.210
And then this one is at 45 degrees.

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:32.560
We call this a cross polarization.

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:34.350
Yeah. So this is what
Einstein's theory sort of said.

00:14:34.350 --> 00:14:35.800
But, again, we didn't really know.

00:14:35.800 --> 00:14:38.570
Is this something real?

00:14:38.570 --> 00:14:44.510
So a little bit later, all back
in -- up in 1959, there was,

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:48.110
after a lot of discussion, included
famous physicist Richard Feynman,

00:14:48.110 --> 00:14:51.940
these guys Bondi, Pirani, and
Robinson published this paper

00:14:51.940 --> 00:14:54.610
that really showed that
you could extract energy

00:14:54.610 --> 00:14:58.640 position:56%
from these gravitational waves and,
therefore, they must be real, right.

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:01.540
And this was basically the
argument that they had.

00:15:01.540 --> 00:15:04.280
So their argument was,
imagine you had a rod and on

00:15:04.280 --> 00:15:06.230
that rod you had some beads.

00:15:06.230 --> 00:15:07.950
And those beads were
a little sticky.

00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:09.710
You know, they basically
were able to slide on the rod

00:15:09.710 --> 00:15:11.260
but they rubbed a little bit.

00:15:11.260 --> 00:15:13.450
And they showed that if you
have a gravitational wave come

00:15:13.450 --> 00:15:16.400
by it makes these beads
go back and forth.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:17.700
Those beads rub on the rod.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:19.000
It heats up the rod.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:20.300
And the rod's warmed up, right?

00:15:20.300 --> 00:15:22.940
And so the fact that energy has
shown up in that rod shows you

00:15:22.940 --> 00:15:25.470
that that energy came from
these gravitational waves.

00:15:25.470 --> 00:15:28.630
It's one of these beautiful thought
experiments that sort of shows.

00:15:28.630 --> 00:15:30.620
And I was trying to actually
build something like that.

00:15:30.620 --> 00:15:33.050
Took, you know, another
40 years, right?

00:15:33.050 --> 00:15:36.610
But, basically, that's
the fundamental idea

00:15:36.610 --> 00:15:37.910
that says, you know what?

00:15:37.910 --> 00:15:40.690
It might actually be possible
to detect these things, okay?

00:15:40.690 --> 00:15:45.840
So, so that was a very important,
important breakthrough as well.

00:15:45.840 --> 00:15:47.740
And at the same time, people
were starting to trying

00:15:47.740 --> 00:15:50.760
to understand well, okay, where
in nature might we actually find

00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:52.060
gravitational waves?

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:56.690 position:56%
So, again, there was this idea that,
well, general relativity was sort

00:15:56.690 --> 00:15:59.060
of interesting for these
very small effects of things

00:15:59.060 --> 00:16:01.920
like [inaudible] shift of Mercury
and deflecting light by the sun.

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:04.000
But it wasn't really
important for astrophysics.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.730
Well, these guys, Peters and
Matthews, in '63, were able to sort

00:16:08.730 --> 00:16:12.310
of do an approximate solution
of Einstein's equations.

00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:13.890
And I'll talk about
it a little bit more.

00:16:13.890 --> 00:16:16.950
But what they basically
showed is for a binary system,

00:16:16.950 --> 00:16:20.400
and binary star systems
of various kinds are one

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:22.270
of the most common
types of star systems

00:16:22.270 --> 00:16:23.570
that we have in the universe.

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:24.880
Most stars are in binaries.

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:26.430
And they showed that
they actually lose energy

00:16:26.430 --> 00:16:28.740
because they'll radiate
gravitational waves

00:16:28.740 --> 00:16:30.570
and that will affect
the orbit of the binary.

00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:32.920
And they made a quantitative
prediction for how fast

00:16:32.920 --> 00:16:34.650
that energy would change

00:16:34.650 --> 00:16:38.100
and basically how strong the
gravitational waves would be.

00:16:38.100 --> 00:16:39.600
So here's the basic idea.

00:16:39.600 --> 00:16:42.470
So I've got two stars or two
black holes or two neutron stars

00:16:42.470 --> 00:16:44.750
or a planet and a star, you
know, whatever you like.

00:16:44.750 --> 00:16:46.490 position:56%
They're orbiting around one another.

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:49.090
And if you work out
Einstein's equations, as Peters

00:16:49.090 --> 00:16:52.030
and Matthews did, you find out
that they, that those stars

00:16:52.030 --> 00:16:54.890
as they orbit will
release energy and momentum

00:16:54.890 --> 00:16:56.560
in the form of gravitational waves.

00:16:56.560 --> 00:16:59.050
Now, that energy has to come from
somewhere, and where it comes

00:16:59.050 --> 00:17:02.490
from is in the orbit
of the two objects.

00:17:02.490 --> 00:17:04.970
So, basically, they fall
closer to one another.

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:07.900
So if you look at Newtonian
mechanics, when they fall closer

00:17:07.900 --> 00:17:09.830
to one another they
have to speed up, right?

00:17:09.830 --> 00:17:13.560
So they speed up and now
they're closer to one another.

00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:14.860
They're moving faster.

00:17:14.860 --> 00:17:17.940
And so the amount of energy
they release is even greater.

00:17:17.940 --> 00:17:20.120
And so you can very quickly see
that this is a runaway process.

00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:22.120
You basically, you know,
lose a little bit of energy.

00:17:22.120 --> 00:17:23.420
You get closer.

00:17:23.420 --> 00:17:24.720
You lose more energy.

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:26.020
You get closer.

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:27.320
You lose more energy.

00:17:27.320 --> 00:17:28.620
You get closer.

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:29.920
And it gets up, up,
up, up, up, up, up.

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:31.220
Until eventually these things
crash into one another.

00:17:31.220 --> 00:17:33.700
Now, Peters and Matthews could
sort of predict by extrapolating

00:17:33.700 --> 00:17:35.680
where they would crash
into one another.

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:36.980
But the math that they used

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:40.170 position:56%
to do this extrapolation didn't work
once you got the things really close

00:17:40.170 --> 00:17:41.470
to one another, right?

00:17:41.470 --> 00:17:43.970
Basically, all these approximations
that they had to use break

00:17:43.970 --> 00:17:47.490
down when they try to get the
stars almost touching, right?

00:17:47.490 --> 00:17:49.570
And so, at least for this
part of it, it's interesting.

00:17:49.570 --> 00:17:51.470
For this part you're going
to need something new.

00:17:51.470 --> 00:17:54.950
And I'll talk about
that in a little bit.

00:17:54.950 --> 00:17:57.820
So then this is what
really kicked off the field.

00:17:57.820 --> 00:17:59.360
And this is a gentleman
that was working

00:17:59.360 --> 00:18:01.250
up at the University of Maryland.

00:18:01.250 --> 00:18:04.100
A very accomplished experimental
physicist named Joseph Weber.

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:08.430
And he starts, basically based on
these ideas from Bondi and others,

00:18:08.430 --> 00:18:10.650
to build gravitational
wave antennas.

00:18:10.650 --> 00:18:12.970
And he calls them these
bar detectors.

00:18:12.970 --> 00:18:17.090
And lo and behold, he
actually claims to see a event.

00:18:17.090 --> 00:18:20.820
And this just sets off the
whole physics community.

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:22.890
So here's basically how
Weber's system he used.

00:18:22.890 --> 00:18:25.010
So he wasn't looking so much
for a binary star system.

00:18:25.010 --> 00:18:28.530
But he was looking for pulsars
which had been recently discovered.

00:18:28.530 --> 00:18:31.570
So pulsar's a rapidly
spinning neutron star.

00:18:31.570 --> 00:18:33.950
And the idea is that the
pulsar has a little bump on it.

00:18:33.950 --> 00:18:36.110
If it's anything other than a
perfect sphere, it's also going

00:18:36.110 --> 00:18:37.810
to radiate gravitational
waves because, basically,

00:18:37.810 --> 00:18:40.460
that bump is going to go whipping
around the top of the pulsar,

00:18:40.460 --> 00:18:42.490
and you're going to get
gravitational waves coming out.

00:18:42.490 --> 00:18:44.110
So that's the idea here.

00:18:44.110 --> 00:18:45.900
And his detector's very simple.

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:48.170
You basically take
a bar of material,

00:18:48.170 --> 00:18:50.480
and you want to have a
material that's got a high

00:18:50.480 --> 00:18:51.780
mechanical quality.

00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:53.400
So something like a
metal or a crystal.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:57.130
You want it to be big so that
it can couple to these waves.

00:18:57.130 --> 00:18:59.560
And you want it to sort of
be isolated, so suspended,

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:01.780
so that it's sort of
free to ring like a bell.

00:19:01.780 --> 00:19:04.420
And if these waves come by and
they happen to have the frequency

00:19:04.420 --> 00:19:06.340
that matches the natural
resonance frequencies

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:08.420 position:56%
of the bar, the bar's going to ring.

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:11.310
And then you just have to
measure the bar ringing.

00:19:11.310 --> 00:19:15.370
Now Weber was a very smart
experimental physicist and he knew

00:19:15.370 --> 00:19:18.350
that there could be other things
that might cause the bar to ring.

00:19:18.350 --> 00:19:19.650
And so he said, aha.

00:19:19.650 --> 00:19:20.950
What I'm going to do is
I'm going to build two bars

00:19:20.950 --> 00:19:22.250
and I'm going to spread them apart.

00:19:22.250 --> 00:19:23.660 position:56%
And I'm going to put one at the
University of Maryland and I'm going

00:19:23.660 --> 00:19:25.610
to put one at Argonne
Lab in Chicago.

00:19:25.610 --> 00:19:28.900 position:56%
And if they're spread that far apart
it's unlikely that there's any kind

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:31.260
of effect that can make both of
them go blip at the same time.

00:19:31.260 --> 00:19:33.910
And when he sees both of them
go blip at the same time,

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:37.210
this is from his paper, he
says, gravitational wave, right?

00:19:37.210 --> 00:19:42.610
So this got people going, you
know, really excited in the field.

00:19:42.610 --> 00:19:44.550
So it generates this
tremendous interest.

00:19:44.550 --> 00:19:46.910
So the astrophysicists all
sort of jump out and say, wait.

00:19:46.910 --> 00:19:49.050
You know, how big could a mountain
be on a pulsar and how many

00:19:49.050 --> 00:19:51.490
of them should there be out
there, and that kind of thing.

00:19:51.490 --> 00:19:54.220
And the experimenters say, well,
I'm going to build a bar, too.

00:19:54.220 --> 00:19:56.830
And there's like a dozen
of these major efforts

00:19:56.830 --> 00:19:58.520
that are built all over the world.

00:19:58.520 --> 00:20:00.170
And nobody finds anything.

00:20:00.170 --> 00:20:02.490
So, first of all, the
astronomers say, you know,

00:20:02.490 --> 00:20:05.020
the rates are just not really
compatible with what you're seeing.

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:06.320
You shouldn't have seen --

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:08.320
because he claims two or
three possible detections.

00:20:08.320 --> 00:20:10.420
And they say, you know, you
just shouldn't see that many.

00:20:10.420 --> 00:20:12.390
And the other people
building the detectors,

00:20:12.390 --> 00:20:13.690
even though they're
actually even starting

00:20:13.690 --> 00:20:15.680
to make little improvements,
they don't see anything.

00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:18.430
And so eventually people
sort of start to decide

00:20:18.430 --> 00:20:21.240
that Weber must be wrong
despite the fact that, yeah,

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:25.030 position:56%
to his death he believed that he had
detected the gravitational waves.

00:20:25.030 --> 00:20:27.070 position:56%
So it's kind of a mixed legacy here.

00:20:27.070 --> 00:20:29.540
So on the one hand, if
it weren't for Weber,

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:31.340
we never would have
gotten all of the interest

00:20:31.340 --> 00:20:34.300
from the astrophysicists and the
experimental physics community.

00:20:34.300 --> 00:20:38.120
And on the other hand, we sort
of got the stigma of, boy,

00:20:38.120 --> 00:20:41.220
we're going to need to have an
absolute gold standard event before

00:20:41.220 --> 00:20:42.840
we ever claim a real detection.

00:20:42.840 --> 00:20:44.220
And so the communities sort

00:20:44.220 --> 00:20:49.230
of really felt the
impact of this gentleman.

00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:53.710
So shortly after this, a gentleman
by the name of Ray Weiss comes

00:20:53.710 --> 00:20:56.320
up with a different kind of
detector based on lasers.

00:20:56.320 --> 00:20:57.620
He's working at MIT.

00:20:57.620 --> 00:20:59.450
Actually, interestingly
enough, it came out later

00:20:59.450 --> 00:21:01.320
that two Soviet scientists had come

00:21:01.320 --> 00:21:04.120
up with a very similar
idea a little bit earlier.

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:07.250 position:56%
And actually this happened -- anyone
that's worked in physics has found

00:21:07.250 --> 00:21:09.210
that during the Cold War
this happened all the time.

00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:12.270
And now there's actually
a lot of, you know,

00:21:12.270 --> 00:21:15.100
former Soviet Bloc physicists that
are working in U.S. institutions.

00:21:15.100 --> 00:21:16.880
And whenever you talk to them,
they say, "You know that so

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:19.610
and so knew this before
the" -- yeah, right.

00:21:19.610 --> 00:21:23.940
There's always the Russian guy
that knew it before we did.

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:25.240
But in any case.

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:26.570
So Weiss makes some
contributions here.

00:21:26.570 --> 00:21:27.870
He built a prototype.

00:21:27.870 --> 00:21:29.170
And really what's important.

00:21:29.170 --> 00:21:31.360
This 1972 paper which is
actually just a publication,

00:21:31.360 --> 00:21:35.520 position:56%
in internal MIT publication, he lays
out the basic fundamentals for one

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:36.890
of these gravitational
wave detectors.

00:21:36.890 --> 00:21:38.620
And this will become the detector

00:21:38.620 --> 00:21:42.410
that eventually makes
the detection in 2015.

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:43.810
So here's the basic idea.

00:21:43.810 --> 00:21:47.500
And this is more modern than
his concept at the time.

00:21:47.500 --> 00:21:48.800
So you have a laser.

00:21:48.800 --> 00:21:51.840
This idea is called an
interferometer, and it dates back

00:21:51.840 --> 00:21:53.920
to this guy named Michaelson
who was working

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:56.160
in the 19th century
looking at ether drift.

00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:58.790
And so I have this laser and I have
this thing called a beam splitter

00:21:58.790 --> 00:22:01.390
which basically divides
a light into two paths.

00:22:01.390 --> 00:22:05.380
And one light goes down this path;
one light goes down this path.

00:22:05.380 --> 00:22:07.020
The purpose of these
mirrors, you basically --

00:22:07.020 --> 00:22:10.350
the light bounces back and forth
between these several times

00:22:10.350 --> 00:22:11.700
or several hundred times.

00:22:11.700 --> 00:22:14.480
It basically effectively makes
the arm lights much bigger.

00:22:14.480 --> 00:22:17.160
And in any event, when
they come back,

00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:18.890
if the arms are exactly
the same length,

00:22:18.890 --> 00:22:21.040
then the light comes
right back to the laser.

00:22:21.040 --> 00:22:23.480
If they're off a little bit,
then some of the light comes

00:22:23.480 --> 00:22:24.820
out to the photo-receiver.

00:22:24.820 --> 00:22:26.120
And you can see from --

00:22:26.120 --> 00:22:28.150
if you remember that cartoon of
how the gravitational wave worked

00:22:28.150 --> 00:22:30.200
where it stretched in one direction
and compressed in the other

00:22:30.200 --> 00:22:33.080
and goes back and forth -- that
this sort of L-shaped detector

00:22:33.080 --> 00:22:35.380
where you measure the difference
between this arm and this arm,

00:22:35.380 --> 00:22:38.590
is sort of perfect kind of antenna
for measuring gravitational wave

00:22:38.590 --> 00:22:39.910
because that's exactly
what it looks for.

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:42.730
It looks for difference in
lengths between these two arms.

00:22:42.730 --> 00:22:45.120
And so that's the basic idea.

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:46.420
So what's the problem?

00:22:46.420 --> 00:22:49.620
So when we work with
gravitational waves we work

00:22:49.620 --> 00:22:51.800
with this thing called
strain, all right?

00:22:51.800 --> 00:22:57.120
So strain, if anybody's in
engineering as I was a while ago,

00:22:57.120 --> 00:22:59.900
is the mechanical quality called
a change in length over length.

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:03.190
And the reason we use strain to
describe how big our waves are is

00:23:03.190 --> 00:23:05.950
because it's space itself
that's stretching, right?

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:09.030
So if I take space and
if I take this cartoon --

00:23:09.030 --> 00:23:10.860
you imagine I made
it twice as big --

00:23:10.860 --> 00:23:12.890
well, then the physical
motion would be twice as big

00:23:12.890 --> 00:23:15.300
because there's twice as much
space between the cartoon.

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:16.940 position:56%
Everything sort of scales up, right?

00:23:16.940 --> 00:23:19.910
So I want to make my detector,
you know, change the length

00:23:19.910 --> 00:23:21.640
over length is what the strain is.

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:25.220
And this is a rough estimate
for how big the strain would be.

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:29.220
So you want to have -- so M
is the mass of the object,

00:23:29.220 --> 00:23:32.030
R is sort of how close the
objects are to one another,

00:23:32.030 --> 00:23:34.270
so you want to have a lot
of mass in a small space.

00:23:34.270 --> 00:23:37.880
D is how far away the objects are,
so you want them relatively close.

00:23:37.880 --> 00:23:39.470
And then you have this
kind of nasty factor

00:23:39.470 --> 00:23:41.170
of G squared over C to the 4th.

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:43.920
So G is Newton's gravity constant.

00:23:43.920 --> 00:23:48.440
That's a number that's like 710
to the minus 11 in standard units.

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:50.430
So that's a tiny number,
and it's squared.

00:23:50.430 --> 00:23:51.950
And C is the speed of light.

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:54.450
That's 10 to the 8
meters per second,

00:23:54.450 --> 00:23:55.750
you know, 10 to the 4th power.

00:23:55.750 --> 00:23:57.890
That's a big number to the
4th power in the denominator.

00:23:57.890 --> 00:23:59.890
So this factor is a killer.

00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:02.120
And so even if you sort of
pick the most optimistic

00:24:02.120 --> 00:24:04.090
after physical values for these,

00:24:04.090 --> 00:24:06.770
you get a number that's
like 10 to the minus 21.

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:09.720
So that's a sextillionth, a
part in a billion trillion.

00:24:09.720 --> 00:24:11.450
Small number.

00:24:11.450 --> 00:24:13.630
So, another way to look at that
is that's about the diameter

00:24:13.630 --> 00:24:17.790
of a hydrogen atom divided by
the distance to the sun, okay?

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:20.960
So that's sort of a reasonable
size amplitude to expect

00:24:20.960 --> 00:24:22.260
for a gravitational wave.

00:24:22.260 --> 00:24:25.180
And that's the point which most
people say, that was interesting.

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:27.390
I'm going to go back to doing
something else [laughter].

00:24:27.390 --> 00:24:30.780
But, people like Weiss,
you know, from the '70s,

00:24:30.780 --> 00:24:32.980
continued to push this, right?

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:35.780
And it eventually became this
thing called LIGO, right?

00:24:35.780 --> 00:24:39.470
So LIGO, the LIGO Project grew
out of this and many other efforts

00:24:39.470 --> 00:24:41.830
around -- so their
efforts around the world,

00:24:41.830 --> 00:24:44.150
and the basically objective
is we're going to really try

00:24:44.150 --> 00:24:45.730
to build something where
we think we've got a chance

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:47.030
of making a detection.

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:48.330
So they built -- it was funded

00:24:48.330 --> 00:24:50.150
by the National Science
Foundation primarily.

00:24:50.150 --> 00:24:51.920
They service some major
contributions

00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:53.310
from international partners.

00:24:53.310 --> 00:24:56.450
And there's two sites
housing four-kilometer-long

00:24:56.450 --> 00:24:57.750
L-shaped detectors.

00:24:57.750 --> 00:24:59.680
So this one is on the
Hanford Nuclear Reservation

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:01.140
in Washington state.

00:25:01.140 --> 00:25:02.550
This one is in Louisiana.

00:25:02.550 --> 00:25:05.380
Actually, this very near where all
this flooding is going on recently.

00:25:05.380 --> 00:25:07.020
Fortunately, the detector
was designed

00:25:07.020 --> 00:25:09.640
to handle a thousand-year-flood,
and it seems to be okay,

00:25:09.640 --> 00:25:11.940
although many of the
employees are obviously

00:25:11.940 --> 00:25:13.800
in great difficulty right now.

00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:16.370
But they started it in 1990.

00:25:16.370 --> 00:25:18.550
A lot of pre-project work
was going on in the '80s.

00:25:18.550 --> 00:25:20.410
It took a while to build it.

00:25:20.410 --> 00:25:23.640
There is a major civil
engineering infrastructure here.

00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:25.350 position:56%
They did their initial science runs.

00:25:25.350 --> 00:25:26.730
Didn't find anything.

00:25:26.730 --> 00:25:28.210
They didn't upgrade
to Advanced LIGO.

00:25:28.210 --> 00:25:30.230
And in 2015 they turned
on Advanced LIGO.

00:25:30.230 --> 00:25:32.530
I think most people know the
story there, but if you don't,

00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:34.360
you'll get it in a few slides.

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:38.790
So, while LIGO was
sort of getting going,

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:40.260
there was another really
important event.

00:25:40.260 --> 00:25:42.190
And, actually, this
could be claimed as sort

00:25:42.190 --> 00:25:43.950
of the first detection
of gravitational waves.

00:25:43.950 --> 00:25:47.680
Those of us that work in building
the gravitational wave instrument

00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:49.820
call this an indirect detection.

00:25:49.820 --> 00:25:51.580
So if you remember
Peters and Matthews,

00:25:51.580 --> 00:25:53.900
this paper from the early '60s,

00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:57.590
had this idea that as you had
two stars orbiting one another,

00:25:57.590 --> 00:26:00.930
they would make gravitational
waves and the orbit would shrink.

00:26:00.930 --> 00:26:05.290
And what Taylor Weisberg actually
did is they had a pulsar system,

00:26:05.290 --> 00:26:07.620
and it was -- it actually turned
out to be a binary pulsar system,

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:10.760
I'll explain what that means in
a moment, that Taylor and one

00:26:10.760 --> 00:26:14.020
of his graduate students
had discovered earlier.

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:16.970
And they noticed that this thing
was actually shrinking, right?

00:26:16.970 --> 00:26:19.520
And it basically was shrinking
at the rate that was predicted

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:22.530
by general relativity, and
due to gravitational waves.

00:26:22.530 --> 00:26:25.300
So that was this really
important paper

00:26:25.300 --> 00:26:27.410
and what we'll show a
little bit more of it here.

00:26:27.410 --> 00:26:29.660
So a pulsar is one of
these neutron stars,

00:26:29.660 --> 00:26:31.600
the same kind of this
Weber was looking for.

00:26:31.600 --> 00:26:36.160
But in this case, a pulsar has a
little radio beam that's pointed

00:26:36.160 --> 00:26:39.270 position:56%
in a direction that's not the same
as the axis of the star spinning it.

00:26:39.270 --> 00:26:41.710
And we actually don't
really know why that --

00:26:41.710 --> 00:26:43.080
the details of why that happens,

00:26:43.080 --> 00:26:45.930
but these are very common
astrophysical objects.

00:26:45.930 --> 00:26:48.900
So if you're a radio astronomer,
you just see this blip going by.

00:26:48.900 --> 00:26:51.690
So if you just look at a patch
of the sky, you see blip, blip,

00:26:51.690 --> 00:26:53.550
blip, blip, blip, blip, right?

00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:54.970
And actually when people
first discovered these,

00:26:54.970 --> 00:26:56.770
they thought they were
seeing alien civilizations

00:26:56.770 --> 00:26:58.600
because it was such a regular tick.

00:26:58.600 --> 00:27:00.220
They said, what could
that possibly be?

00:27:00.220 --> 00:27:04.470
Well, it turns out it's a
sort of collapse core of star

00:27:04.470 --> 00:27:07.880
with this radio beam coming out of
it, and it's spinning quite fast.

00:27:07.880 --> 00:27:10.970
And it's got so much
rotational inertia, so much mass,

00:27:10.970 --> 00:27:13.900
that there's really nothing that
can affect its spin very much.

00:27:13.900 --> 00:27:16.030
And so it's a very good clock.

00:27:16.030 --> 00:27:19.430
Now binary pulsars -- imagine
this thing is pulsing but happens

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:22.520
to be orbiting another neutron star
that's, let's say, not pulsing.

00:27:22.520 --> 00:27:24.820
And all you can measure
are these pulses.

00:27:24.820 --> 00:27:28.530
But just by timing these pulses,
and if you look over enough time,

00:27:28.530 --> 00:27:30.330
and you're clever enough,
you can actually figure

00:27:30.330 --> 00:27:32.040 position:56%
out all the parameters of the orbit.

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:33.430
So you can figure out
the masses of the stars.

00:27:33.430 --> 00:27:34.730
You can figure out the separations.

00:27:34.730 --> 00:27:36.540
You know where they are,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:27:36.540 --> 00:27:38.690
Then you can just plug into
Peter and Matthew's formula

00:27:38.690 --> 00:27:42.570
and you can say, you know, how
should the orbit evolve over time?

00:27:42.570 --> 00:27:45.450
And the answer is that line.

00:27:45.450 --> 00:27:48.020
And the dots are the measurements.

00:27:48.020 --> 00:27:50.420
Now if you're in -- if
you ever teach in --

00:27:50.420 --> 00:27:52.080
I think someone we had was a
high school teacher, right?

00:27:52.080 --> 00:27:55.580
If someone does lab and they gave
you this, you'd say, you cheated.

00:27:55.580 --> 00:27:57.100
You moved your measurements, right?

00:27:57.100 --> 00:27:58.400
But they didn't.

00:27:58.400 --> 00:27:59.910
And for this they get
the Nobel Prize.

00:27:59.910 --> 00:28:03.290
The interesting this is that
Weisberg, the guy that did a lot

00:28:03.290 --> 00:28:06.360
of the calculations on the paper,
doesn't get the Nobel Prize.

00:28:06.360 --> 00:28:09.490
But Holz, the guy that
discovered the pulsar, does.

00:28:09.490 --> 00:28:13.640
So it's just sort of the vagaries
of the Nobel Prize system.

00:28:13.640 --> 00:28:17.960
But, anyways, this is sort of,
you know, really is the last nail

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:20.850
in the coffin of the gravitational
wave question, are they real?

00:28:20.850 --> 00:28:24.580
Because here we're seeing the
effect of gravitational waves

00:28:24.580 --> 00:28:27.540
on a binary star system
in nature, right, so.

00:28:27.540 --> 00:28:29.490
But, again, we're not really
measuring the waves themselves.

00:28:29.490 --> 00:28:32.650
We're seeing that the waves are
sucking energy out of the system.

00:28:32.650 --> 00:28:34.760
Okay. So now I'm going to jump

00:28:34.760 --> 00:28:37.860
up into something a
little bit more modern.

00:28:37.860 --> 00:28:42.260
And so that is a paper, actually,
by one of my colleagues, John Baker

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:44.530
and Joan Centrella, and
several others at Goddard.

00:28:44.530 --> 00:28:46.330
There were other groups
around the world.

00:28:46.330 --> 00:28:49.160
And what they were trying to
do is they were trying to --

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:50.770
again, going back to
Peters and Matthews.

00:28:50.770 --> 00:28:54.220
They had this, this -- equations
worked sort of for the early part

00:28:54.220 --> 00:28:56.590
of these stars spinning
around one another.

00:28:56.590 --> 00:28:59.630
But these equations broke down
when you got really close.

00:28:59.630 --> 00:29:01.100
And that's because
Einstein's equations,

00:29:01.100 --> 00:29:04.210
there is no close form solution
for two stars orbiting one another.

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:05.510
It's called the two-body problem.

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:07.310
So in Newtonian mechanics
you can work it out.

00:29:07.310 --> 00:29:08.610
Keppler worked it out.

00:29:08.610 --> 00:29:11.630
And if you try to do it in
Einstein's equations, you know,

00:29:11.630 --> 00:29:14.790
you can do it -- approximate
solutions for certain situations

00:29:14.790 --> 00:29:17.240
like widely separated stars,
but when you get all the way

00:29:17.240 --> 00:29:18.540
down to the stars, you know,

00:29:18.540 --> 00:29:21.070
orbiting one another really
close, it doesn't work.

00:29:21.070 --> 00:29:22.410
So the only way you can do this is

00:29:22.410 --> 00:29:24.220
by a thing called numerical
relativity.

00:29:24.220 --> 00:29:26.120
So you basically chop
up Einstein's equations

00:29:26.120 --> 00:29:27.660
and you solve them
in a super computer.

00:29:27.660 --> 00:29:30.690
And this is a very
technical computing challenge.

00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:33.150
It took about 20 years for
people to be able to do this.

00:29:33.150 --> 00:29:37.040
And this sort of an
illustration of two black holes,

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:39.510
their gravitational waves, their
trajectories, and if you're sitting

00:29:39.510 --> 00:29:41.510
in the front, you might be
able to see some of these grids

00:29:41.510 --> 00:29:44.770
which are the computational
meshes that are being used

00:29:44.770 --> 00:29:48.840
to compute Einstein's
equations on a grid there.

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:50.140
So what did they see.

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:51.440
So this isn't exactly
from their paper,

00:29:51.440 --> 00:29:54.250
but this is a kind of
representative thing.

00:29:54.250 --> 00:29:56.570
This is the waveform.

00:29:56.570 --> 00:29:59.580
And so you see it goes up and down
and up and down and up and down.

00:29:59.580 --> 00:30:02.280
Now this part back here
is basically what Peters

00:30:02.280 --> 00:30:03.580
and Matthews were seeing, right,

00:30:03.580 --> 00:30:05.040
the fact that you have
these things oscillating.

00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:08.630
You get this sort of
sinusoidal gravitational wave.

00:30:08.630 --> 00:30:11.150
And if you look carefully you
see that both the frequency

00:30:11.150 --> 00:30:12.450
of the wave gets close --

00:30:12.450 --> 00:30:15.980
gets higher, which means basically
the waves get closer together,

00:30:15.980 --> 00:30:17.280
right?

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:18.580
So you see them getting
scrunched together.

00:30:18.580 --> 00:30:20.970 position:56%
And you see that the height of wave,
or the amplitude of the wave goes

00:30:20.970 --> 00:30:23.390
up until it reaches its maximum.

00:30:23.390 --> 00:30:27.620
Now we call this a chirp because if
you were to try to make this sound,

00:30:27.620 --> 00:30:30.340
or you play this through, it goes
from low frequency/low amplitude

00:30:30.340 --> 00:30:31.650
to a higher frequency amplitude.

00:30:31.650 --> 00:30:34.000
So it goes whoooooop, right?

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:36.750
And that's exactly what a
gravitational wave sounds like,

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:38.050
right?

00:30:38.050 --> 00:30:39.370
And it was -- numerical
relativity was needed

00:30:39.370 --> 00:30:40.730
to get this detail, right?

00:30:40.730 --> 00:30:42.520
So this is what we needed
a super computer for.

00:30:42.520 --> 00:30:44.720
This you could do,
you know, kind of,

00:30:44.720 --> 00:30:46.200
kind of with that Peters
and Matthews formula.

00:30:46.200 --> 00:30:47.500
This starts to get a little harder.

00:30:47.500 --> 00:30:50.440
And when you get up to this part,
you need to have a super computer.

00:30:50.440 --> 00:30:53.140
And so the other important
about these wave forms is

00:30:53.140 --> 00:30:55.140
that they can encode
astrophysical information.

00:30:55.140 --> 00:30:59.680
So the precise rate at which this
thing rises up tells you something

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:02.140
about the mass of the
system that's involved.

00:31:02.140 --> 00:31:04.220 position:56%
And there's other kinds of
information you can figure out from,

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:05.600
say, those two different
polarizations.

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:07.160
This is just plotting
one polarization.

00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:09.040
But if you plot the other
polarization, you can figure

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:11.620
out the angle of the
system, and the distance,

00:31:11.620 --> 00:31:13.460 position:56%
and all kinds of interesting things.

00:31:13.460 --> 00:31:16.060
So this really critical for
being able to do science

00:31:16.060 --> 00:31:19.220
with the gravitational waves as
opposed to just detecting them.

