00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:46.340
of general relativity
that's conceivable.

00:42:46.340 --> 00:42:48.690
So if you really want to understand
if gravity's going to break,

00:42:48.690 --> 00:42:49.990
it's going to break here, right?

00:42:49.990 --> 00:42:51.730
So this is where you want
to understand gravity.

00:42:51.730 --> 00:42:56.940
You can also do some more sort of
traditional astronomy if you will

00:42:56.940 --> 00:43:01.530
where we can get a census of
actually millions of these binaries

00:43:01.530 --> 00:43:03.060 position:56%
in the, what we call close binaries,

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:04.510
which are things we
know from x-ray studies.

00:43:04.510 --> 00:43:07.930
Actually many of those black holes
that were in that chart before,

00:43:07.930 --> 00:43:10.670
these kinds of stars that
are in our own Milky Way.

00:43:10.670 --> 00:43:12.340
But they're all emitting
gravitational waves.

00:43:12.340 --> 00:43:15.250 position:56%
And this actually kind of makes this
cacophony of millions of sources

00:43:15.250 --> 00:43:16.550
that are all on top of one another

00:43:16.550 --> 00:43:17.970
and it's a big data
analysis challenge to try

00:43:17.970 --> 00:43:19.270
to pick the individual ones out.

00:43:19.270 --> 00:43:21.830
But we think we could pick
out maybe 10s of thousands

00:43:21.830 --> 00:43:23.130
and actually do things like --

00:43:23.130 --> 00:43:24.550
they'll tell you, well
how many black hole,

00:43:24.550 --> 00:43:26.790
black hole binaries are
there in the Milky Way

00:43:26.790 --> 00:43:28.490
versus neutron star
black hole binaries

00:43:28.490 --> 00:43:30.170
versus white dwarf,
white dwarf binaries?

00:43:30.170 --> 00:43:32.280
You know, these kind of things
that astronomers are interested in.

00:43:32.280 --> 00:43:34.810
And we could maybe even do things
like try to map the milky way

00:43:34.810 --> 00:43:36.340
in white dwarf binaries, you know?

00:43:36.340 --> 00:43:39.720
How does that distribution in the
galaxies differ from the stars?

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:42.480
So this is really -- you know, and
another really interesting thing is

00:43:42.480 --> 00:43:45.000
that there's 14 of these
objects that are know right now.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.780
So that is they're physical
really known objects

00:43:47.780 --> 00:43:49.690
which we could point to in a sky.

00:43:49.690 --> 00:43:51.820
And you can calculate, you know,

00:43:51.820 --> 00:43:54.760
how big is a gravitational
wave, and could LISA see them?

00:43:54.760 --> 00:43:57.500
And, in fact, LISA could
see them quite easily.

00:43:57.500 --> 00:43:58.870
So their source is like guaranteed.

00:43:58.870 --> 00:44:00.660
You turn them on and they're
just there because they're

00:44:00.660 --> 00:44:02.510
on all the time, these stars.

00:44:02.510 --> 00:44:04.690
And then, of course, there's
the unexpected sources.

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:07.190
So maybe really exotic physics,

00:44:07.190 --> 00:44:11.220
maybe some exotic astrophysics,
or who knows what?

00:44:11.220 --> 00:44:13.320
So that's why we'd like to do this.

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:15.340
So why are we doing this
thing called LISA Pathfinder?

00:44:15.340 --> 00:44:19.140
And I like to call it, for this
thing I call picophobia, right?

00:44:19.140 --> 00:44:21.650
So this is basically the --
and I made up this definition.

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:22.950
You won't find this.

00:44:22.950 --> 00:44:24.360
But this is the extreme
or irrational fear

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:26.560
of large negative exponents,
especially when related

00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:27.860
to engineering requirements.

00:44:27.860 --> 00:44:32.190
So in a place like LIGO, I mean,
yes, many engineers were involved,

00:44:32.190 --> 00:44:34.170
but it was really driven
by experimental physicists.

00:44:34.170 --> 00:44:36.650 position:56%
When you go to do something in space
flight, you really don't want people

00:44:36.650 --> 00:44:39.170
like me, you know, the
physicists, in there,

00:44:39.170 --> 00:44:40.470
you know, building the spacecraft.

00:44:40.470 --> 00:44:42.090
You want the engineers doing
it because they're going

00:44:42.090 --> 00:44:44.450
to do it right, and it's not
going to blow up on the launch pad

00:44:44.450 --> 00:44:47.050
or not going to break, you
know, halfway up there.

00:44:47.050 --> 00:44:49.260
So you need to be able to
communicate these requirements.

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:51.050
And a lot of times, you
know, we go and we say, well,

00:44:51.050 --> 00:44:52.680
we need to keep this thing
stable to a picometer.

00:44:52.680 --> 00:44:53.990
And they go, what's a picometer?

00:44:53.990 --> 00:44:59.230
So, really, there's some sort of
this thought that doing something

00:44:59.230 --> 00:45:01.050
like LISA was just too hard.

00:45:01.050 --> 00:45:04.640
So instead of doing
LISA we did this.

00:45:04.640 --> 00:45:06.030
We cut out one arm.

00:45:06.030 --> 00:45:07.360
We put it in a single spacecraft.

00:45:07.360 --> 00:45:09.200
We shrunk it down so it
fit in a single spacecraft.

00:45:09.200 --> 00:45:11.280
And we got this thing
called LISA Pathfinder.

00:45:11.280 --> 00:45:15.320
So LISA Pathfinder is two test
masses with a laser interferometer

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:17.300
between them it's like
this big, right?

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:19.450
So two test masses,
laser interferometer.

00:45:19.450 --> 00:45:22.190
So when you do this,
you actually get rid

00:45:22.190 --> 00:45:23.490
of all your gravitational
wave signal

00:45:23.490 --> 00:45:25.160
and you keep all of your noise.

00:45:25.160 --> 00:45:27.680
So if you're an astronomer,
that's a bad deal, right?

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:29.530
We keep all the noise
and lose all the signal.

00:45:29.530 --> 00:45:31.920
If you're an instrument scientist,
that's actually a pretty good deal

00:45:31.920 --> 00:45:33.660
because you want to
understand the noise, right?

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:37.520 position:56%
And so for the instrument scientist
this really lets us understand well,

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:39.590
how well can we put this
test mass in free fall?

00:45:39.590 --> 00:45:42.150
How well can we measure the
distances between these things?

00:45:42.150 --> 00:45:43.910
And is it good enough
so that if we scaled it

00:45:43.910 --> 00:45:46.760 position:56%
up to the full detector we could
make the gravitational reproduction.

00:45:46.760 --> 00:45:50.500
So here's this idea
of drag-free control.

00:45:50.500 --> 00:45:52.990
So when we get up in space,
we have this little cube.

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:56.240
Actually, I have some little
plastic models I can pull

00:45:56.240 --> 00:45:58.570
out in the Question
and Answer period.

00:45:58.570 --> 00:46:01.590
So you have this cube and we
let it go inside the spacecraft.

00:46:01.590 --> 00:46:02.990
So it's actually in a little cavity

00:46:02.990 --> 00:46:04.510
in the spacecraft, and
it's freely falling.

00:46:04.510 --> 00:46:06.570
So it's not touching
the spacecraft at all.

00:46:06.570 --> 00:46:09.130
So imagine that something comes
and pushes on the spacecraft

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:11.260
like let's say the
solar wind is a big one.

00:46:11.260 --> 00:46:14.620 position:56%
Well now the spacecraft is no longer
in free fall, and it will start

00:46:14.620 --> 00:46:16.870
to move towards the test mass
and eventually crash into it.

00:46:16.870 --> 00:46:19.170
But we have a sensor
system that senses that

00:46:19.170 --> 00:46:21.730
and we have a thruster system
that can -- counteracts that.

00:46:21.730 --> 00:46:24.810
And we fly in balance
around that test mass.

00:46:24.810 --> 00:46:27.780
And so I like to think of it as a
flying shield that sort of flies

00:46:27.780 --> 00:46:29.620
around the test mass
and shields it from kind

00:46:29.620 --> 00:46:31.830
of any external disturbances.

00:46:31.830 --> 00:46:34.620
So that's the idea
of drag-free control.

00:46:34.620 --> 00:46:35.920
So what does things look like?

00:46:35.920 --> 00:46:37.220
So here are their challenges.

00:46:37.220 --> 00:46:38.520
So here's our test masses.

00:46:38.520 --> 00:46:41.960
We need to isolate them from forces
and we express our requirement

00:46:41.960 --> 00:46:45.050
in acceleration, so 1G, 10
meters per second squared,

00:46:45.050 --> 00:46:47.020
is acceleration on Earth.

00:46:47.020 --> 00:46:50.490
We want to do femto-G, 10
to the minus 15 of that.

00:46:50.490 --> 00:46:53.620 position:56%
We need to have thrusters that can
push this several-hundred-kilograms'

00:46:53.620 --> 00:46:54.920
spacecraft around.

00:46:54.920 --> 00:46:58.380
They thrust with precisions
at sort of sub-micro-Newton.

00:46:58.380 --> 00:47:00.820
So their total thrust is
in a micro-Newton range.

00:47:00.820 --> 00:47:03.420
That's about the weight
of a mosquito in 1G.

00:47:03.420 --> 00:47:05.890
And their fluctuation is
10th of a micro-Newton

00:47:05.890 --> 00:47:07.190
or hundredths of a micro-Newton.

00:47:07.190 --> 00:47:08.990
That's the weight of the
mosquito's antennae, right?

00:47:08.990 --> 00:47:10.290
So that's the kind of fluctuation.

00:47:10.290 --> 00:47:11.980
An inkjet printer has a thrust

00:47:11.980 --> 00:47:13.880
of about a hundred
micro-Newtons, right?

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:15.690
So these are tiny,
tiny little thrusters.

00:47:15.690 --> 00:47:17.070
But they have to be very precise.

00:47:17.070 --> 00:47:19.200
We have to do this precision
optometricalogy [assumed spelling],

00:47:19.200 --> 00:47:21.400
so here we see during
one of the integration,

00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:26.190
this is that interferometer
picture from back here.

00:47:26.190 --> 00:47:28.360
That one. So that's what
it really looks like.

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:30.400
And then, of course,
the spacecraft itself --

00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:32.120
this is really where
that picophobia comes in.

00:47:32.120 --> 00:47:35.520
You have to keep track of it
thermally and magnetically

00:47:35.520 --> 00:47:36.820
and all those kinds of things.

00:47:36.820 --> 00:47:38.120
And one really interesting
thing is you have

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:39.420 position:56%
to keep track of it gravitationally.

00:47:39.420 --> 00:47:41.670
And that means we need to know
the mass of every single part

00:47:41.670 --> 00:47:43.360
that we put around
because the own --

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:46.100
the gravity of the spacecraft
itself actually pulls those test

00:47:46.100 --> 00:47:47.400
masses around.

00:47:47.400 --> 00:47:48.700
And we have to keep those balanced,

00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:50.340
otherwise they were going
to fall into the walls.

00:47:50.340 --> 00:47:52.290
And, for instance, see
these little blue things?

00:47:52.290 --> 00:47:55.210
These are little zip-ties, little
cable-ties, that are holding cables

00:47:55.210 --> 00:47:56.920
that are going to the
photoreceivers.

00:47:56.920 --> 00:47:58.810
Well, we care about the
mass of those things.

00:47:58.810 --> 00:48:00.910
Not because they're going
to keep the spacecraft from,

00:48:00.910 --> 00:48:02.280
you know, being able to launch.

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:04.510
We care about the mass because
they're going to pull the test mass

00:48:04.510 --> 00:48:05.960
around from their own gravity.

00:48:05.960 --> 00:48:10.360
So what they had to do was
they would weigh each zip-tie,

00:48:10.360 --> 00:48:14.150
put it on there, zip it, clip
the end off, weight the clip,

00:48:14.150 --> 00:48:16.170
write down the difference, and
say that's how much mass I left

00:48:16.170 --> 00:48:18.930
in there, and then add that
to their gravity model.

00:48:18.930 --> 00:48:20.370
And I mean, it's just incredible.

00:48:20.370 --> 00:48:22.830
That's the kind of
engineering that we had to do.

00:48:22.830 --> 00:48:25.870
So here's some pretty pictures
of -- here's integration.

00:48:25.870 --> 00:48:27.450
So this shows you the
scale of this thing.

00:48:27.450 --> 00:48:28.820
It's actually pretty small.

