00:48:53.690 --> 00:48:54.990
And, let's see.

00:48:54.990 --> 00:48:57.350
What do we do in LISA Pathfinder?

00:48:57.350 --> 00:49:01.060
So, basically, what we do is we've
been running European payloads

00:49:01.060 --> 00:49:04.180
which actually several of us in the
U.S. are actual -- also working on.

00:49:04.180 --> 00:49:05.840
I ran from March to June.

00:49:05.840 --> 00:49:07.790
The NASA payload's
running right now.

00:49:07.790 --> 00:49:10.070
And there's a mission
extension that just approved.

00:49:10.070 --> 00:49:13.160
It will run through -- from
October 30 to next May.

00:49:13.160 --> 00:49:16.820
And what we basically do is
we do two modes of operation.

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:19.420
In one mode of operation we sort
of sit there and measure the noise.

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:21.840
So we want to see how well did
we place these tests masses

00:49:21.840 --> 00:49:23.390
in free fall, right?

00:49:23.390 --> 00:49:25.990
And on another mode, we do
experiments where we try

00:49:25.990 --> 00:49:27.870
to understand, well,
what's causing the noise?

00:49:27.870 --> 00:49:29.710
So we maybe deliberately
make something worse.

00:49:29.710 --> 00:49:31.950
So like we change the
temperature and we see,

00:49:31.950 --> 00:49:33.250
does that make the test mass move?

00:49:33.250 --> 00:49:34.810
And we sort of make these
deliberate couplings

00:49:34.810 --> 00:49:36.140
to understand all the noise.

00:49:36.140 --> 00:49:38.680
And eventually we want to build
this thing we call a noise budget

00:49:38.680 --> 00:49:40.640
where you have all the
different contributions that --

00:49:40.640 --> 00:49:42.200
and this is just, you
know, four of them.

00:49:42.200 --> 00:49:43.990
But there's like 50 of them.

00:49:43.990 --> 00:49:46.390
And we do experiments to understand
all these different things

00:49:46.390 --> 00:49:52.010
so that we basically have a model
that we then checked against a --

00:49:52.010 --> 00:49:55.650
against a flight [inaudible] --
against a real piece of hardware.

00:49:55.650 --> 00:49:58.190
And now we have a lot of confidence
that if we go to build LISA --

00:49:58.190 --> 00:50:00.840
and we say well what if we make
the temperature like this instead

00:50:00.840 --> 00:50:02.310
of like that, or make
the magnetic field

00:50:02.310 --> 00:50:03.610
like this instead of like that?

00:50:03.610 --> 00:50:06.320
We understand that this -- we can
use that model that's been checked

00:50:06.320 --> 00:50:08.900
against reality to build
the next instrument

00:50:08.900 --> 00:50:10.200
and have a lot of confidence.

00:50:10.200 --> 00:50:11.500
And this is just sort of cute.

00:50:11.500 --> 00:50:12.990
This is the way it
