00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:29.500
So what's the big result?

00:50:29.500 --> 00:50:31.710
So this is the big result
that came out of that paper.

00:50:31.710 --> 00:50:34.300
It's a little technical,
but since it is our result,

00:50:34.300 --> 00:50:36.750
I wanted to try to go through it.

00:50:36.750 --> 00:50:39.140
So, basically this is a plot

00:50:39.140 --> 00:50:42.910
where on the vertical axis
here you have the acceleration,

00:50:42.910 --> 00:50:44.210
and it's in these funny units

00:50:44.210 --> 00:50:46.100
of meters per second
squared per root hertz,

00:50:46.100 --> 00:50:47.630
so forget about the --
figure out the units.

00:50:47.630 --> 00:50:49.890
But meters per second
squared is acceleration.

00:50:49.890 --> 00:50:53.290
And it's basically saying how
much acceleration do you have

00:50:53.290 --> 00:50:54.820
from ideal perfect free fall?

00:50:54.820 --> 00:50:57.580
And these numbers are
in a logarithmic scale.

00:50:57.580 --> 00:51:00.300
So this is 10 to the
minus 12, so a trillionth.

00:51:00.300 --> 00:51:01.600
This is a 10th of a trillionth.

00:51:01.600 --> 00:51:03.320 position:56%
This is a hundredth of a trillionth.

00:51:03.320 --> 00:51:09.210 position:56%
And this is whatever the thousandth
of a trillionth is -- quadrillionth.

00:51:09.210 --> 00:51:12.190 position:56%
So that's the size of these numbers.

00:51:12.190 --> 00:51:14.490
And then over here is
basically frequency.

00:51:14.490 --> 00:51:17.860
So this is saying if I have
fluctuations in the acceleration,

00:51:17.860 --> 00:51:19.320
how fast are those fluctuations?

00:51:19.320 --> 00:51:22.950
So the main point of this is
that you want things to be low.

00:51:22.950 --> 00:51:25.130
So the lower they are
on this, the better.

00:51:25.130 --> 00:51:27.190
And the -- and going from here

00:51:27.190 --> 00:51:28.850
to here is a factor
of 10 better, right?

00:51:28.850 --> 00:51:30.870
And from here to here is
another factor of 10 better.

00:51:30.870 --> 00:51:32.360
That's a logarithmic scale.

00:51:32.360 --> 00:51:35.280
So this orange line here
is where we said we wanted

00:51:35.280 --> 00:51:36.580
to go for LISA Pathfinder.

00:51:36.580 --> 00:51:37.880
It was a tech demo.

00:51:37.880 --> 00:51:39.780
We weren't going to try to get
to the full mission performance.

00:51:39.780 --> 00:51:43.680
The green line here is where
