01:02:20.260 --> 01:02:22.380
And the gravitational waves would
be a good way to look at it.

01:02:22.380 --> 01:02:25.070
So that's an example sort
of exotic astrophysics.

01:02:25.070 --> 01:02:26.370
There could also be exotic physics.

01:02:26.370 --> 01:02:30.420
So if you come up with these exotic
theories like cosmic strings,

01:02:30.420 --> 01:02:33.480
you know, almost all of them
couple to gravity in some way.

01:02:33.480 --> 01:02:35.880
And so there's ideas of like
if you have cosmic strings

01:02:35.880 --> 01:02:38.160
that have little kinks in
them and those kinks relax,

01:02:38.160 --> 01:02:40.420
they'll produce a little
burst of gravitational waves.

01:02:40.420 --> 01:02:41.730
We could go look for those.

01:02:41.730 --> 01:02:45.420
I would try to, you know, build
a whole detector to do that.

01:02:45.420 --> 01:02:46.720
Well, I would.

01:02:46.720 --> 01:02:48.220
But I wouldn't be able
to get the money to do it

01:02:48.220 --> 01:02:49.770
because it's kind of speculative.

01:02:49.770 --> 01:02:53.480
But, you know, it's hard to
predict what you're going to see.

01:02:53.480 --> 01:02:56.320
So I think broadly speaking
it's, you know, you know,

01:02:56.320 --> 01:02:59.020
astrophysics surprises
and physics surprises.

01:02:59.020 --> 01:03:02.070
And we've got a good chance of
getting after both of those.

01:03:02.070 --> 01:03:03.730
There one's in here.

01:03:03.730 --> 01:03:08.370
&gt;&gt; If you happen to be looking at
one of these colliding black holes

01:03:08.370 --> 01:03:10.530
that you're seeing gravitationally
with an optical telescope

01:03:10.530 --> 01:03:13.010
or a radio telescope, would
you have seen anything?

01:03:13.010 --> 01:03:14.310
&gt;&gt; Ira Thorpe: Okay.

01:03:14.310 --> 01:03:15.610
Excellent, excellent,
excellent question.

01:03:15.610 --> 01:03:16.910
So the question is,
could you see anything

01:03:16.910 --> 01:03:18.390
with electromagnetic telescope?

01:03:18.390 --> 01:03:21.830
So, the answer is, in
principle, in principle, yes.

01:03:21.830 --> 01:03:23.420
Okay? So it really has
to do with the sources.

01:03:23.420 --> 01:03:25.370
And it's actually something that
we'd really like to go after.

01:03:25.370 --> 01:03:27.400
We call it multi-messenger
astronomy.

01:03:27.400 --> 01:03:29.980
So there's this big idea of
multi-wavelength astronomy

01:03:29.980 --> 01:03:33.010
where I look at the same kind of
object with radio waves and optical

01:03:33.010 --> 01:03:35.860
and UV and all kinds of
things, and I put the sort

01:03:35.860 --> 01:03:38.300
of full-color picture together
to understand the object.

01:03:38.300 --> 01:03:40.700
Here is the idea is if we could
look at gravitational waves

01:03:40.700 --> 01:03:42.550
and electromagnetic
waves at the same time,

01:03:42.550 --> 01:03:45.370
I've got completely different and
kind of complimentary channels

01:03:45.370 --> 01:03:48.650
of information that I can
use to understand a system.

01:03:48.650 --> 01:03:51.590
Now for the system that LIGO
saw, it's two black holes.

01:03:51.590 --> 01:03:53.240
And black holes are pure gravity

01:03:53.240 --> 01:03:55.970
and they basically don't emit
electromagnetic radiation, right?

01:03:55.970 --> 01:03:59.160
So you wouldn't expect that any
kind of telescope could see one.

01:03:59.160 --> 01:04:02.910 position:56%
Now that said, black holes in nature
are often surrounded by some kind

01:04:02.910 --> 01:04:08.200
of gas of something, and they might
make some sort of something, right,

01:04:08.200 --> 01:04:09.550
some little burst, right?

01:04:09.550 --> 01:04:12.160
And there actually are people
that were working to try

01:04:12.160 --> 01:04:13.760
to follow up these events.

01:04:13.760 --> 01:04:17.590
And there was a sort of tentative
maybe correlation with a,

01:04:17.590 --> 01:04:20.460
with some gamma rays that were
detected by the Fermi mission.

01:04:20.460 --> 01:04:23.340
I think it's probably unlikely
that that was actually correlated,

01:04:23.340 --> 01:04:27.350
but it was a very, very, very
interesting, interesting paper.

01:04:27.350 --> 01:04:30.390
Now, when LIGO starts detecting
things like neutron stars --

01:04:30.390 --> 01:04:31.800
so there's a little
bit less massive.

01:04:31.800 --> 01:04:33.310
They're going to need a
little bit more sensitivity

01:04:33.310 --> 01:04:34.940
to have a good chance of
detecting those things.

01:04:34.940 --> 01:04:36.790
But that's one of the things
they're really going after.

01:04:36.790 --> 01:04:38.640
Neutron stars are made
out of matter.

01:04:38.640 --> 01:04:41.320
They're very similar to black holes
but they're made out of matter.

01:04:41.320 --> 01:04:43.150
And when they crash
into one another --

01:04:43.150 --> 01:04:46.340
we have a very high confidence that
they produce, if they're pointed

01:04:46.340 --> 01:04:49.140
at us, they produce gamma ray
bursts which we can see to the --

01:04:49.140 --> 01:04:52.870
way father than we could detect
the gravitational waves from LIGO.

01:04:52.870 --> 01:04:55.030
Or, if we're seeing them
from some other angle,

01:04:55.030 --> 01:04:57.050
they might produce a
sort of small super nova.

01:04:57.050 --> 01:04:58.350
I think about a kilanova.

01:04:58.350 --> 01:04:59.880
And people are trying
to go after that, too.

01:04:59.880 --> 01:05:02.860
So once LIGO starts
seeing gravitational waves

01:05:02.860 --> 01:05:05.920
from neutron stars, there will
be a lot of opportunity for that.

01:05:05.920 --> 01:05:08.110
And with LISA, there's
also lots of opportunities.

01:05:08.110 --> 01:05:10.290
But that's the long answer, okay?

01:05:10.290 --> 01:05:11.590 position:56%
That's exactly what we'd like to do,

01:05:11.590 --> 01:05:16.120
is we'd like to do
multi-messenger astronomy.

01:05:16.120 --> 01:05:18.290 position:56%
Maybe there's one here in the front.

