roughly 50-50 partnerships.

01:06:07.340 --> 01:06:10.350 position:56%
Now the technology demonstrator sort
of started to drag on a little bit.

01:06:10.350 --> 01:06:12.500
There were some funding
problems on the NASA side,

01:06:12.500 --> 01:06:14.610
some technical problems
on both sides.

01:06:14.610 --> 01:06:16.800
And basically, the Europeans
doubled-down on their funding

01:06:16.800 --> 01:06:19.900
and spent like 10 times more
money than they were expecting to.

01:06:19.900 --> 01:06:22.640 position:56%
And NASA kind of cut if off and
said we're only going to do so much.

01:06:22.640 --> 01:06:27.240
So for Pathfinder, it's almost
like an 80-20 kind of expenditure

01:06:27.240 --> 01:06:31.750
in terms of 20% NASA
and 80% European.

01:06:31.750 --> 01:06:33.360
Now then, at the same time,

01:06:33.360 --> 01:06:34.980
we were still holding
together this idea we're going

01:06:34.980 --> 01:06:38.900
to do an equal partnership with
the Europeans on LISA and --

01:06:38.900 --> 01:06:41.740
but back in 2011, NASA
had to kind of --

01:06:41.740 --> 01:06:44.120
we basically had to pull out
because we didn't have the budget.

01:06:44.120 --> 01:06:46.170
And so then the Europeans
said well, we're going to try

01:06:46.170 --> 01:06:47.940
to make the detector a
little less capable and see

01:06:47.940 --> 01:06:49.270
if we can do it on our own.

01:06:49.270 --> 01:06:51.570
They've been pushing that idea
for the last several years.

01:06:51.570 --> 01:06:55.730
And now they're starting to make
it look a little bit more real.

01:06:55.730 --> 01:07:00.190
They've gotten a selection, but
with a nominal launch date in 2034,

01:07:00.190 --> 01:07:02.030
which is kind of long
for a lot of us.

01:07:02.030 --> 01:07:05.970
And now with all the interesting
gravitational waves there's renewed

01:07:05.970 --> 01:07:09.080
interest in the U.S. The
Europeans certainly could use some

01:07:09.080 --> 01:07:10.380
financial help.

01:07:10.380 --> 01:07:12.660
I think we could also
provide some technical help.

01:07:12.660 --> 01:07:14.650
And we're trying to work with
Europeans to figure out what kind

01:07:14.650 --> 01:07:17.570
of share the U.S. can play.

01:07:17.570 --> 01:07:21.740
And actually this report I just
mentioned in the National Academy

01:07:21.740 --> 01:07:25.850
that just came out like last week,
was a review of the decadal survey.

01:07:25.850 --> 01:07:28.990 position:56%
So the decadal surveys are things
that set policies for space science.

01:07:28.990 --> 01:07:31.140
And one of their main
recommendations was the U.S. should

01:07:31.140 --> 01:07:35.890
get back into LISA at the majority
-- you know, at that sort of,

01:07:35.890 --> 01:07:38.770
you know, a significant role.

01:07:38.770 --> 01:07:41.220
So that's all playing
out now in the politics.

01:07:41.220 --> 01:07:45.300
But I think it's pretty likely
that we'll have a significant role.

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:46.820
&gt;&gt; But one follow-up.

