01:08:45.860 --> 01:08:49.270
to this information in
the way that the result is

01:08:49.270 --> 01:08:53.790
that Albert becomes this iconic
figure of the 20th century?

01:08:53.790 --> 01:08:56.070
&gt;&gt; Ira Thorpe: So the question
is, why did the public react

01:08:56.070 --> 01:08:57.560
to the prediction of --

01:08:57.560 --> 01:09:01.210
the verification of
Einstein's prediction?

01:09:01.210 --> 01:09:05.980
I mean, I think because it was just
-- it was such a wacky prediction.

01:09:05.980 --> 01:09:09.410
And to have it actually come
true was just sort of amazing.

01:09:09.410 --> 01:09:12.680
I mean, people have this -- I think
largely due to this Einstein --

01:09:12.680 --> 01:09:14.230
they have this idea that
that's how science works.

01:09:14.230 --> 01:09:16.070
That sort of people
sit and they say, well,

01:09:16.070 --> 01:09:17.370
I'm going to make a
theory and I'm going

01:09:17.370 --> 01:09:18.670
to predict what's going to happen.

01:09:18.670 --> 01:09:19.970
And then somebody goes
out and measures it.

01:09:19.970 --> 01:09:21.270
That almost never happens.

01:09:21.270 --> 01:09:22.990
It usually is the complete
opposite way.

01:09:22.990 --> 01:09:24.290
We go and measure something.

01:09:24.290 --> 01:09:25.590
We go, what the heck was that?

01:09:25.590 --> 01:09:28.060 position:56%
And then the theorists have to
figure out, you know, what it meant.

01:09:28.060 --> 01:09:29.720
And it's only those rare cases

01:09:29.720 --> 01:09:32.280
where people make a prediction
that's very outlandish

01:09:32.280 --> 01:09:36.590
and then it takes a long time and a
significant effort to go verify it,

01:09:36.590 --> 01:09:39.770
that people really become,
you know, lauded and famous.

01:09:39.770 --> 01:09:42.170
And Einstein's the
key example of that.

